{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17539234","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17539234"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:39:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:39:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16499"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16499","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16499"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.26,0.22,0.34,0.06,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9190"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109315"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9190","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9190"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16499"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91679"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"3354"},{"type":"tags","id":"3416"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21801"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21802"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37256"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43946"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109315","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109315"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a five-month history of progressive abdominal bloating, excessive flatulence, loose stools and fatigue. She has a history of Roux-en-Y gastric bypass surgery and takes multivitamins and iron supplementation. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her abdomen is soft and mildly distended but non-tender. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 102 g/L (115-165) \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMean cell volume 102 fL (80-96) \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVitamin B12 180 pmol/L (200-680)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFerritin 85 \u00b5g/L (20-200)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStool microscopy and culture negative for pathogens\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFaecal calprotectin is 35 \u00b5g/g (\u0026lt;50)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELactulose breath test shows an early rise in hydrogen levels\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Low FODMAP diet","Rifaximin","Oral vitamin B12 supplementation","Probiotics","H. pylori eradication therapy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features highly suggestive of small intestinal bacterial overgrowth (SIBO), including chronic bloating, diarrhoea, weight loss, and macrocytic anaemia with B12 deficiency. SIBO occurs when there is an abnormal increase in the total number of bacteria, and/or changes in the types of bacteria present in the small intestine. Her risk factors include altered anatomy from gastric bypass surgery. The diagnosis is confirmed by a positive lactulose breath test.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERifaximin\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first-line treatment for SIBO. It is a non-absorbable antibiotic with broad-spectrum coverage against both aerobic and anaerobic bacteria. Its minimal systemic absorption means it has an excellent safety profile and fewer side effects compared to systemic antibiotics. It is also worth noting however that this form of treatment is quite costly and may not be accessible to all patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile they may be trialled to provide symptomatic relief, there is no strong evidence for the role of a \u003Cstrong\u003Elow FODMAP diet\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Eprobiotics\u003C/strong\u003E in the management of SIBO.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough \u003Cstrong\u003EB12 replacement\u003C/strong\u003E will be necessary, given the severity of her anaemia and malabsorption issues parenteral administration would be more appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EH. pylori eradication therapy\u003C/strong\u003E would not be appropriate as there is no evidence of H. pylori infection, and the symptoms are clearly explained by SIBO. H. pylori is diagnosed through a urea breath test, rather than a carbohydrate breath test.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Rifaximin is the first-line treatment for small intestinal bacterial overgrowth due to its minimal systemic absorption and broad-spectrum coverage","Small intestinal bacterial overgrowth should be considered in patients with risk factors who present with chronic bloating, diarrhoea and malabsorption","Anatomical changes to the small intestine are a significant risk factor for small intestinal bacterial overgrowth"],"references":["Pimentel M, Saad RJ, Long MD, Rao SSC. ACG Clinical Guideline: Small Intestinal Bacterial Overgrowth. Official journal of the American College of Gastroenterology | ACG [Internet]. 2020;115(2). Available from: https://journals.lww.com/ajg/fulltext/2020/02000/acg_clinical_guideline__small_intestinal_bacterial.9.aspx","Ahmed JF, Padam P, Ruban A. Aetiology, diagnosis and management of small intestinal bacterial overgrowth. Frontline Gastroenterol. 2022 Jul 12;14(2):149-154. doi: 10.1136/flgastro-2022-102163. PMID: 36818787; PMCID: PMC9933597. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36818787/","Sorathia SJ, Chippa V, Rivas JM. Small Intestinal Bacterial Overgrowth. 2023 Apr 17. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan\u2013. PMID: 31536241. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31536241/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91679"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16499"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91679","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91679"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-19T20:32:37+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-19T20:33:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9190"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109315"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"73","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/73"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Post-graduate","synonyms":null,"description":"Not suitable for a medical student","position":2,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},